  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">COVID-19 Response - Support to Surveillance, Risk Communication and Points of Entry</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Component 1: Based on identified gaps in community-level awareness leading to a reluctance to take precautions against the spread of COVID-19 in Afghanistan inclusive of a reluctance to adhere to movement restrictions, physical distancing measures and testing for sick or suspect persons, IOM proposes to expand community level risk communication and engagement through the deployment of social mobilizers in the provinces of Nangahar, Kandahar, Nimroz and Herat- four disease outbreak hubs linked to cross border returns. These teams will engage with Community Health Worker networks to ensure regular advocacy through organized sensitization campaigning with a focus on peri-urban and rural areas where information gaps remain the most pronounced. Special attention will be paid to community and religious leadership cadres.


Component 2: In discussion and agreement with the Public Health Directors in Herat, Nangarhar, Kandahar and Nimroz provinces and the health cluster/WHO in both regions, IOM will supplement existing rapid response teams (COVID sample collection teams composed of 1 doctor, 1 nurse and 1 lab tech as per the SOP developed by the Ministry of Health) by adding 11 additional teams (35 medical personnel in total) to respond to requests to collect and process COVID-19 samples from suspect cases. In order to transport these teams IOM will support their movements with ambulances which will also be used for referral to designated government isolation/hospital facilities for suspect and emergency cases.</narrative>
  </description>
